Name: Block_Data_Structure
Fieldvalues.Name:
The Block Data Structure is set up as defined in GTIS. The Block Data Structure is used to determine the number of memory blocks that make up the claibration as well as the size of each block. The BDS is used by the tool to ensure an entire calibration is built. BDS is also used by tools to perform the download function. Some restrictions do apply to this structure. See applicable GTIS version for restrictions. This item is created in its own C file, block_data.c



The data in the BDS is modified as part of the build process. To verify the correctness of this data it is necessary to view it in the .srec or .cal files after building.

Name: CAGT_Block_Fault_Codes
FolderName: To be used only when no acronym is known for the item.\
Fieldvalues.Name:
Array of fault codes to be blocked. Fault codes can be found in CES14602 specification.
Size of this array and hence the maximum number of faults that can be blocked, can be changed by setting the value of CAGT_Faults_To_Block via "Configurable data" tab in a given build configuration.
Build script limits the value of CAGT_Faults_To_Block to 30.
In this array, if a fault code is listed after a zero entry, that fault code will not be blocked.
E.g Lets say CAGT_Faults_To_Block has been over-ridden to 5 via "Configurable data" tab in a given build configuration.
Now if, CAGT_Block_Fault_Codes[1] =valid FC1, CAGT_Block_Fault_Codes[2]=valid FC2, CAGT_Block_Fault_Codes[3]=0, CAGT_Block_Fault_Codes[4]=valid FC3,
CAGT_Block_Fault_Codes[5]=valid FC4;
In above case, only FC1 and FC2 will be considered for fault blocking.

Name: CAGT_Edc_Item_List_Array

Each entry in this list contains the following:
1. item_id_or_addr: Public data ID or address of the variable to be recorded via Data Collector2.

Name: CFTR_ErrorIndexTable
Fieldvalues.Name:
List of error indices whose status is either active, inactive, or pending. An active error is one that is currently being experienced and has persisted in time. An inactive error is one that is no longer currently being experienced but has a fault count, as stored in the GTIS_Fault_Count_Table, of at least one. A pending error is one that is currently being experienced but has not yet persisted in time. Only active errors will be translated into faults by the communications translator.

If an element (error_index) is removed from the list then the software shall use a value of zero to indicate that the array element can be overwritten by the next error that has transitioned to pending. Therefore the first zero in the array indicates an available slot for storing the error_index.

Name: CFTR_Error_Persistence_Time
Fieldvalues.Name:
This array is indexed with error_index and contains an instance of time (ECM_Run_Time) when the following occurs:



1. The corresponding value of CFTR_Fault_Status_Table[array_index] is ACTIVE and the CFTR_Error_Status_Table bit that maps to the CFTR_Error_Index_Table[array_index] changes from ""set"" to ""clear"". The time is recorded to allow for a countown to the INACTIVE state.



OR



2. The corresponding value of CFTR_Fault_Status_Table[array_index] goes to INACTIVE. In this case the time is held to allow a countown for the removal of the entries of the corresponding error_index in the CFTR_Error_Index_Table.



This is a powerdown table set dynamically while the code is executed.



The maximum size of this array is 255 elements.

B Type Size is filled in by build scripts (see gen_config_tracker_tables.pm)

Name: CFTR_Error_Status_Table
Fieldvalues.Name:
Table that records the status of errors in the system. Error status can be determined by any component through the use of the services CMGR_get_error_index(); and CMGR_get_error();. It is indexed by system error index number.



An error status of 0 means no error.

An error status of 1 means error exists.

Name: CFTR_Fault_Count_Table
Fieldvalues.Name:
This array contains the current fault count for each fault that is currently active in the system. The fault count for each error is incremented each time the ACTIVE state is entered for each fault status table error entry.

The index into this array is associated with a system error by means of the error index into the CFTR_Error_Index_Table.



This array is limited to 255 elements.

Name: CFTR_Fault_Status_Mismatch_Ctr
Fieldvalues.Name:
This indicates that how many times there was mismatch in the CFTR_Fault_Status_Table.Every error in the CFTR_ErrorIndexTable is searched in the ECM_Active_Error_Index and ECM_InActive_Error_Index.

If the error is found in the ECM_Active_Error_Index then the status for the error in the CFTR_Fault_Status_Table should be ACTIVE. If the status for the error in the CFTR_Fault_Status_Table is not ACTIVE then the count is incremented and the errors removed from the tables.

Similarly for an error in ECM_InActive_Error_Index if the corresponding status in not INACTIVE in the CFTR_Fault_Status_Table the count is incremented and the errors removed from the tables.

This variable is just for Engineering Testing only.

Name: CFTR_Fault_Status_Table
Fieldvalues.Name:
This array contains the current error state for each fault that is currently active in the system. The index into this array is associated with a system error by means of the error index into the CFTR_Error_Index_Table.



The valid error states are defined as the following:



[b7??..b0]

PENDING xx01xxx0

ACTIVE xx00xxx1

INACTIVE xx00xxx0

ACTIVE_PENDING xx11xxx1

INACTIVE_PENDING xx11xxx0

SNAPSHOT xxxxxx1x

NO_SNAPSHOT xxxxxx0x

COUNTDOWN_MODE x1xxxxxx

ELAPSED_TIME_MODE x0xxxxxx







This array has a maximum of 255 elements.

Name: CFTR_SystemLatchErrorTable
Fieldvalues.Name:
Table that latches the status of errors in the system. It is indexed by system error index number.

An error status of 0 means no error.
An error status of 1 means error exists.

Name: CFTR_Table_Inactive_Mismatch_Ctr
Fieldvalues.Name:
This indicates that how many times there was mismatch in ECM_Inactive_Error_Index and CFTR_ErrorIndexTable.
This variable is just for Engineering Testing only.

Name: CFTR_Table_Mismatch_Counter
Fieldvalues.Name:
This indicates that how many times there was mismatch in ECM_Active_Error_Index and CFTR_ErrorIndexTable.
This variable is just for Engineering Testing only.

Name: C_ATIC35_0_Channel_1_Slew_Rate
FolderName: To be used only when no acronym is known for the item.\
Fieldvalues.Name:
There are four programmable slew rate setting that are set to a given range based off load characteristics. The slew rate setting defines both a voltage and current slew rate range. The range should be set to suit the voltage and current slope control for the load.

Bit value dv/dt (V/us) di/dt (A/us) Ton/off (us) Application
00 = 0.2 - 0.8 0.005 - 0.25 <= 34 PWM,low EMI loads
01 = 0.6 - 2.4 0.15 - 0.75 <= 17 PWM,low EMI loads
10 = 1.8 - 7.2 0.45 - 2.3 <= 7 Zenered loads
11 = 5.4 - 22 1.4 - 7.0 <= 4 Time Critical

Name: C_ATIC94_0_Channel_1_Slew_Rate
FolderName: To be used only when no acronym is known for the item.\
Fieldvalues.Name:
The slew rate setting is used to control the turn on/off times to help reduce EMI emmission. Slew rate settings are set based off an output classification of the load. O2 probe heater and solenoids fall into Class A. Class B consist of injector values and other solenoids, and Class C loads consist of start relays, main relays, fuel pump releays, and other loads. The table below defines slew rate setting for Class A and B loads. Class C loads just use on fixed slew rate setting defined as ????????

Bit value dv/dt (V/us)
00 = 0.6 - 1.2
01 = 2.0 - 6.4
10 = 2.0 - 6.0
11 = 6.0 - 20

The priority of Auxiliary Ndot contributions for Inertia_Index and Driveline_Stability_Index.



Acceleration references are resolved in the following fashion: If a reference's priority is set to 100, that reference shall be ignored by Machine manager. Otherwise, the reference with the highest priority shall win.

Fieldvalues.Name: This array can be populated with Public Data IDs or Addresses that are of interest to the user.  During runtime the status of these parameters will be indicated in the bitmask H_BitmapParamsStatus

Name: C_BitmapParamsConfig
FolderName: To be used only when no acronym is known for the item.\
Fieldvalues.Name:
This parameter works with C_BitmapParams to retrieve data that the user specifies. This parameter is a bit map and works the following way.

Starting from left to right

Bit 1: Determines if data specifed in C_BitmapParams is a Public Data ID or is an address.
0 = Public Data ID
1 = Address


Bits 2,3 and 4: Indicated the length of data to retrieve.
0 = not valid - error will be generated
1 = one byte will be retrieved
2 = two bytes will be retrieved
3 = three bytes will be retrieved
4 = four bytes will be retrieved


Bits 5-16: Indicates an offset from the value specifed in C_BitmapParams. This offset can be applied to Public Data IDs and addresses.

Name: C_CFTR_Countdown_Mode
Fieldvalues.Name:
A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. It stores the countdown mode of each error id. The mode will be used to determine how much time will elapse for an error associated fault that has been inactive, to be removed from all tables. Specifically, this is done by using calibratible elapsed time and countdown rate, stored in C_DIR_Fault_Countdown_Period.



There are four modes; mode 0, 1, 2, and 3. Faults in mode 0 can only be cleared by a tool command and therefore will not have a supported calibration for elapsed time and countdown rate.

Name: C_CFTR_J1587ErrorMappingEnable
Fieldvalues.Name: This is a list of Enable bits associated with the entries in CFTR_J1587ErrorMappingTable. The first two bytes reflect the data size in bytes. The bitmapping starts with the second byte (index 1) and begins from the right (rightmost position is for error 0, which is an unused error index).

Name: C_CFTR_J1939ErrorMappingEnable
Fieldvalues.Name: This is a list of Enable bits associated with the entries in CFTR_J1939ErrorMappingTable. The first two bytes reflect the data size in bytes. The bitmapping starts with the second byte (index 1) and begins from the right (rightmost position is for error 0, which is an unused error index).

Name: C_CFTR_Last_Snapshot
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. It stores the boolean status of whether to log a snapshot record if the system error, error id, reoccurs. If the boolean satus is TRUE (1) then the snapshot record of this reoccurring  error id will be logged  in the last occurrence section of the snapshot table.

Name: C_Collector_Interrupt_Options
Fieldvalues.Name:
The interrupt options that are available to use by the Data Collector.

The data collection is done based on the options included in this array. If for a system a particular option is not valid and needs to be removed then all the entries in the table need to be moved 1 place up and an entry of 0xff needs to be added at the end.

E.g. On a system which does not have _ROAD_SPEED_INTERRUPT the entry needs to be removed from the table during calibration to disable data collection based on _ROAD_SPEED_INTERRUPT.

If a system supports data collection on some other events it can be added to the list by replacing the last empty entry.
The empty entries are marked as 0xff in the array.

Name: C_DIR_Fault_Countdown_Period
Fieldvalues.Name:
This parameter is a structure containing 6 time intervals. Two intervals are used for each of trhree countdown modes. The first entry identifies the time that must elapse before fault countdown may begin for mode 1,the second entry is used for mode 2, and the third is used for mode 3. the fourth entry is the coundown rate after the initial coundown time has expired for mode 1. The fifth entrie is used for mode 2. The sixth entrie is used for mode 3.



The definition of its type is:



typedef

{

EB28 elapsed_time_mode_1; /* min=0. , max= 500000 seconds */

EB28 elapsed_time_mode_2; /* min=0. , max= 500000 seconds */

EB28 elapsed_time_mode_3; /* min=0. , max= 500000 seconds */

EB28 countdown_rate_mode_1; /* min=0. , max= 500000 seconds/count */

EB28 countdown_rate_mode_2; /* min=0. , max= 500000 seconds/count */

EB28 countdown_rate_mode_3; /* min=0. , max= 500000 seconds/count */

} fault_countdown_

Name: C_EDC_Collector_Mode_Options
Fieldvalues.Name:
The mode options those are available for the Data collector2.
The data collection is done based on the options included in this array. If for a system a particular option is not valid and needs to be removed then all the entries in the table need to be moved 1 place up and an entry of 0xff needs to be added at the end.
E.g. On a system which does not have _PRE_TRIGGER the entry needs to be removed from the table during calibration to disable data collection based on _PRE_TRIGGER.
If a system supports data collection on some other mode it can be added to the list by replacing the last empty entry. The empty entries are marked as 0xff in the array.

Name: C_ENGN_Friction_Spd_Constant

It is used to estimate friction torque using Chen and Flynn model. This is a part of effort where torque to fuel tables are replaced by polynomial based calculations.

Friction Torque = C_ENGN_Friction_Trq_Constant + C_ENGN_Friction_Spd_Constant * Mean Piston Speed

Fieldvalues.Name: If a value of PDOS is above this severity threshold, then the charge manager will not calculate a speed (RPM) derate based on PDOS.""

Name: C_EPD_TDP_RPM_Thd

Name: C_EPD_TDP_SD_Delay_Time

Name: C_ESM_SensorSupplyErrThrshld1
Fieldvalues.Name:
This is the error counter threshold for the ESM_SensorSupplyError1 value.

This value is compared against a running count of the errors found for the sensor supply #1. When an error on sensor supply #1 is found, then the comparison value is incremented. When there is no error on sensor supply #1, then the comparison value is decremented. The comparison value can never be less than zero.



When the comparison value exceeds this calibration value, then the sensor is considered to be not working correctly and its value should be ignored. The value of ESM_SensorSupplyError1 will be set to DATA_ERROR_NO_VALUE to indicate this condition.

Name: C_Eng_Des_Op_Speed_Asymmetry_Adj
Fieldvalues.Name:
This is utilized in transmission gear selection routines and indicates the engine's preference of lower versus higher engine speeds should its desired speed not be achievable. This is a scaled ratio such that 125 represents an equal preference for a speed lower or higher that the engine's indicated desired speed. The higher the asymmetry adjustment value is above 125, the more the engine prefers to be operated at or above its indicated desired speed. Conversely, the

lower the asymmetry adjustment value is below 125, the more the engine prefers to operate at or below its indicated desired speed. Typically, the engine's asymmetry adjustment will be predicated on fuel consumption considerations, and under these conditions, the method for computing the asymmetry adjustment is indicated in Figure 5. The engine may include other factors into its asymmetry adjustment calculation such as temperatures, pressures, and other operating parameters.

Ties between references of equal priority are resolved by the choosing of the lowest high idle request.

This is a bitmapped value.

bit1 => Enable gateway feature on port 2
bit2 => Enable gateway feature on port 3

Gateway feature, when enabled, must be enabled on atleast two ports.

Name: C_J1939_AMB_AmbAirTmptrSource
Fieldvalues.Name:
This parameter determines the source for the broadcast of Ambient Air Temperature (SPN 171).

Possible Values:

0 - Broadcast ""Not Available""

1 - (Default) Broadcast OEM_Ambient_Air_Tmptr if enabled only

2 - Broadcast Ambient Air Temperature only if only ""Air Temperature"" channel ( T_AIP_AirTmptrRLOC) is used. If this sensor fails, no estimated value will be used as backup.

3 - Broadcast Ambient Air Temperature only if both ""Air Temperature"" and ""Compressor Inlet Temperature"" channels (T_AIP_AirTmptrRLOC and T_AIP_CompInTmptrRLOC) are used. If ""Air Temperature"" channel fails, the estimated value will be used as backup.

Name: C_J1979_Mode09_VID_Support
Fieldvalues.Name:
This calibration is used to indicate and publicize our support of J1979 Vehicle InfoTypes. 0x62A => Support of all RELEVENT Vehicle Infotypes:

VID Support Description
1 0 MsgCnt VIN (N/A)
2 1 VIN
3 0 MsgCnt Cal-ID (N/A)
4 1 Cal-ID
5 0 MsgCnt CVN (N/A)
6 1 CVN
7 0 MsgCnt IPT (N/A)
8 0 IPT for spark ignition
9 0 MsgCnt ECU Name (N/A)
A 1 ECU Name
B 1 In-Use Perf Tracking
0C-FF is reserved.

Bit1 - Fuel system monitoring supported
Bit2 - Comprehensive component monitoring supported
Bit3 - Compression ignition monitoring supported

Name: C_J1979_PID01_NonCont_Mntr_Support
Fieldvalues.Name:
Specifies support for J1979 PID1 non-continous monitors (bitmap):
Bit0: NMHC catalyst monitoring
Bit1: NOx aftertreatment monitoring
Bit2: ISO/SAE reserved (bit shall be set to 0)
Bit3: Boost pressure system monitoring
Bit4: ISO/SAE reserved (bit shall be set to 0)
Bit5: Exhaust gas sensor monitoring
Bit6: PM filter monitoring
Bit7: EGR and/or VVT system monitoring

Name: C_J1979_PID13_Location_Of_O2_Sensors
Fieldvalues.Name:
Specifies location of oxygen sensors, where sensor1 is closest to the engine. Each bit indicates the presence or absence of an oxygen sensor at the given location (bitmap):
Bit0: Bank 1 - Sensor 1 present
Bit1: Bank 1 - Sensor 2 present
Bit2: Bank 1 - Sensor 3 present
Bit3: Bank 1 - Sensor 4 present
Bit4: Bank 2 - Sensor 1 present
Bit5: Bank 2 - Sensor 2 present
Bit6: Bank 2 - Sensor 3 present
Bit7: Bank 2 - Sensor 4 present

Name: C_J1979_PID65_Aux_IO_Support

Specifies support for J1979 PID65 Auxiliary Input/Outputs (bitmap):
Bit0: PTO Status
Bit1: Auto Trans Neutral Gear Status
Bit2: Manual Trans Neutral Gear Status
Bit3: Glow Plug Lamp Status
Bit4-7: ISO/SAE reserved (bit shall be set to 0)

Name: C_J1979_PID69_EGR_Sys_Data_Support
Fieldvalues.Name:
Specifies support for J1979 PID69 EGR System Data(bitmap):
Bit0: Commanded EGR A Duty Cycle/Position
Bit1: Actual EGR A Duty Cycle/Position
Bit2: EGR A Error
Bit3: Commanded EGR B Duty Cycle/Position
Bit4: Actual EGR B Duty Cycle/Position
Bit5: EGR B Error
Bit6-7: ISO/SAE reserved (bit shall be set to 0)

Bit0: EGR Tempterature Bank 1, Sensor 1
Bit1: EGR Tempterature Bank 1, Sensor 2
Bit2: EGR Tempterature Bank 2, Sensor 1
Bit3: EGR Tempterature Bank 2, Sensor 2
Bit4-7: ISO/SAE reserved (bit shall be set to 0)

Bit1: Relative Throttle A Position
Bit2: Commanded Throttle Actuator B Control
Bit3: Relative Throttle B Position
Bit4-7: ISO/SAE reserved (bit shall be set to 0)

Name: C_J1979_PID6D_Fuel_Press_Data_Support

Bit1: Fuel Rail Pressure A

Name: C_NDOT_Filter_Coeff_a1
Fieldvalues.Name:
This coefficient represents the a1 scalar that is used in a governor torque filter that is represented by the following equation.







If we let



X0 = input

X1 = input * z -1 (delayed once)

X2 = input * z -1 * z -1 (delayed twice)

Y = filtered output



Y = (X0 - a1*X1 - a2*X2)b0 + X1*b1 + X2*b2

Name: C_OBD_ClearConfirmLim
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. This is reference to the number of warmup cycles or Engine Hours or Distance that every OBD Error must complete without being active before clearing the confirmed status.

Name: C_OBD_ClearConfirmType
Fieldvalues.Name:
A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. This parameter indicates whether an alternative to warmup cycles is used to clear the OBD confirmed status.

Possible values are:
0 - Warmup Cycle
1 - Engine Hours
2 - Distance

Name: C_OBD_ClearTripsComplete
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. This is reference to the number of operation cycles every OBD Error must complete without being active before clearing the pending status.

Name: C_OBD_ClearTripsNoSimilarCond
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. This is reference to the number of operation cycles that must pass without error before clearing the Fuel Systems OBD error pending status, when similar conditions are not observed.

Name: C_OBD_ClearTripsNotComplete
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. This is reference to the number of operation cycles that must pass without error, before clearing the OBD error pending status, when insufficient monitor completions are achieved.

Name: C_OBD_ConfirmTrips
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index. This is reference to number of trips required to confirm any OBD error.

Name: C_OBD_Derate_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: When this calibratible is equal to 1 ,then only derates are calculated and applied.

Name: C_OBD_DisablePermanent
Fieldvalues.Name: When C_OBD_DisablePermanent is enabled, all 'OBD XX Error Permanent' attribute will be set equal to False when Erase_OBD_Faults call occurs.

Name: C_OBD_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: This is the feature enable for On Board Diagnostic. When set to TRUE, all OBD data like operation cycles, warmupcycles, MIL Status,etc., are updated except OBD_Pending_Errorindex which is independent of this enable.

Name: C_OBD_EngSpdIdleOffset
Fieldvalues.Name: This is the Idle Engine_Speed  offset for incrementing the Number of Ignition Cycles.

Name: C_OBD_Group_Monitor_Supported
Fieldvalues.Name:
This will represent whether particular Monitor group is supported or not for external diagnostics.
0= Supported
1= Not Supported

Monitor Group:

BOOST_PRESS_SYSTEM 1
EGR_WT_SYSTEM 2
EX_GAS_SENSOR 3
FUEL_SYSTEM 4
MIS_FIRE 5
NMHC_CATALYST 6
NOX_AFTER_TREATMENT 7
PM_FILTER 8
FALSE 0

Name: C_OBD_HW_MIL_Diagnostic_En
Fieldvalues.Name:
This calibratible will decide whether MIL Bulb diagnostic in the OBD Fault Handler is required or not.

Possible values are:
0 - MIL diagnostic is disabled
1 - MIL diagnostic is enabled

Note:- If this calibratable is Enabled then, the MIL circuit shall be monitored for malfunctions that cause the lamp to fail to lluminate when commanded on (e.g., burned out bulb).

Name: C_OBD_HighSevErrDur
Fieldvalues.Name: If the OBD_EPD error is active for more than this duration then Net Engine Torque is upper bounded by HighSevPrcntTrqLim for that particular error.This is one dimensional array whose index is same as that of error index.

Name: C_OBD_HighSevPrcntTrqLim
Fieldvalues.Name: If OBD_EPD error is active for more than HighSevErrDur then Net Engine Torque is upper bounded by this value for that particular error.This is one dimensional array whose index is same as that of error index.

Name: C_OBD_IM_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: Enable for OBD Idle Monitor

Name: C_OBD_Idle_Engine_Spd_thd
Fieldvalues.Name:
Engine Speed Idle upper limit offset required to determine OBD Idle condition .
Maximum OBD Idle Speed = C_OBD_Warmup_Idle_Eng_Spd_ref + C_OBD_Idle_Engine_Spd_thd (200 rpm)

Name: C_OBD_Idle_Speed_Offset
Fieldvalues.Name: This is a offset to be added for LSI reference speed.

Name: C_OBD_Idle_Vehicle_Spd_thd
Fieldvalues.Name: Maximum Vehicle Speed offset required to determine OBD Idle condition .

Name: C_OBD_IgnitionCycEngStartDur
Fieldvalues.Name: Duration of time that must elapse after engine startup before incrementing the OBD ignition cycle counter.

Name: C_OBD_J1939_Compliance
Fieldvalues.Name: Indication of OBD Compliance level.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_AccumFuelCoef
Fieldvalues.Name: Coefficient associated with Accumulated_Fuel for the OBD Cooling System Monitor Coolant_Temperature_Prediction expression.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_CHT_Coef
Fieldvalues.Name: Coefficient associated with Charge Temperature for the OBD Cooling System Monitor Coolant_Temperature_Prediction expression.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_ColdDisableTime
Fieldvalues.Name: Amount of time that the Cooling System Monitor may be Disabled due to cold ambient temperature.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Constant_Value
Fieldvalues.Name: Constant value associated with  the OBD Cooling System Monitor Coolant_Temperature_Prediction expression.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Disable_Thd
Fieldvalues.Name: If ambient temperature is below this value, the Cooling System Monitor is Disabled and no decision is made for that trip.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: Enables the OBD Cooling System Monitor

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_EngIdleDutyCycle
Fieldvalues.Name: If the engine is at idle for more than this percent of engine running time, the OBD Cooling System Monitor will delay its decision.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Initial_CT_Coef
Fieldvalues.Name: Coefficient associated with Initial_Coolant_Temperature for the OBD Cooling System Monitor Coolant_Temperature_Prediction expression.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_StartRPM_DlyThd
Fieldvalues.Name: Engine_Speed must reach this value before the OBD Cooling System Monitor Startup Delay Timer will begin timing.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Start_Delay_Time
Fieldvalues.Name:
Amount of time that must pass after Engine_Speed reaches C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_StartRPM_DlyThd
before the OBD Cooling System Monitor will begin functioning.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Start_Temp_Thd
Fieldvalues.Name: At engine startup, if Coolant_Temperature is below this value, the Cooling System Monitor will function. If above, the Monitor will be suspended with no decision being made for that engine start cycle.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Temp_Thd
Fieldvalues.Name: If Coolant_Temperature reaches this value before the Cooling System Monitor's estimated value, the Monitor will determine the Cooling System is Nominal.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CSM_Type_Select
Fieldvalues.Name: Selects which temperature sensor will be used to Disable the Cooling System Monitor due to cold ambient start temperature. 0 = Coolant_Temperature, 1 = Ambient_Air_Tmptr.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: Enable for OBD Coolant Temperature

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_IRL_Clear_Time
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Coolant Temperature In Range Low error is cleared.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_IRL_MinSpd
Fieldvalues.Name: Minimum Speed required to run IR Low algorithm.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_IRL_MinTmptr
Fieldvalues.Name: The Lower Threshold for Coolant Temperature IR Low diagnostic. After Engine is Warmed-Up, If Coolant Temperatures drops below this threshold value for C_OBD_LUCL_CT_IRL_Set_Time amount of time, IR Low Error shall be set.""

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_IRL_Set_Time
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Coolant Temperature In Range Low error is triggered based on Coolant Temperature being below Low Calibrated Threshold.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_MinDeltaTmptrThd
Fieldvalues.Name: The Delta Threshold for Coolant Temperature dither check. While Engine is Warmming-Up, If Coolant Temperatures does not change, (CT_Max _ CT Min) delta is less than this Calibration for C_OBD_LUCL_CT_Stuck_Set_Time amount of time, Stuck Error shall be set.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_Stuck_Clear_Time
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Coolant Temperature Stuck In Range error is cleared.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_Stuck_Min_Trq
Fieldvalues.Name: Minimum torque added for Pause condition, Net_Engine_Torque should be greater than this calibration so as to run Stuck monitor other wise Stuck monitor will be in Pause state.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_CT_Stuck_Set_Time
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Coolant Temperature Stuck In Range error is triggered based on Coolant Temperature does not change by the Calibrated amount.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_Max_Time_Tbl
Fieldvalues.Name:
This calibratible table represents the maximum amount of time that the OBD Cooling System Monitor will be allowed to run, based on Coolant Temperature at engine start.
There are up to 6 elements in this table.
AxisX.Name: This calibratible table represents the values of Coolant_Temperature corresponding to the value in the C_OBD_LUCL_Max_Time_Tbl. Together, these tables represent the maximum amount of time that the OBD Cooling System Monitor will be allowed to run, based on Coolant Temperature at engine start. There are up to 6 elements in this table.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OP_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: Indicates whether the OBD diagnostic for Oil Pressure sensor is enabled in the ECM. This parameter should not be adjustable to users.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OP_IRH_Err_Dur
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Oil Pressure In Range High error is triggered based on Oil Pressure being exceeds an upper bound that is calculated as a function of Engine Speed.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OP_IRL_Err_Dur
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Oil Pressure In Range Low error is triggered based on Oil Pressure being below a lower bound that is calculated as a function of Engine Speed.

1 -severity based

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OP_Win_Timer_Dur
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the length of a watch window for Stuck In Range detection. Within the window, minimum and maximum oil pressure as well as minimum and maximum engine speeds are updated, and used to evaluate if there is a Stuck In Range possibility.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OT_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: Indicates whether the OBD diagnostic for Oil Temperature sensor is enabled in the ECM. This parameter should not be adjustable to users.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OT_IRH_Err_Dur
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Oil Temperature In Range High error is triggered based on Oil Temperature being exceeds an upper bound that is calculated as a function of Coolant Temperature.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OT_IRL_Err_Dur
Fieldvalues.Name: This cal will identify the amount of time that shall elapse before Oil Temperature In Range Low error is triggered based on Oil Temperature being below a lower bound that is calculated as a function of Coolant Temperature.

AxisX.Name: This calibratible table represents the values of Coolant Temperature corresponding to the Oil Temperature lower bound value in the C_OBD_LUCL_OT_Lbnd_LkpTbl_Y. Together, they make the Coolant Temperature vs Oil Temperature lower bound lookup table.

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OT_SIR_CT_Dthr_Thd

Name: C_OBD_LUCL_OT_SIR_Err_Dur

Name: C_SFD_TFR_Box_10_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: A calibratable parameter indicating the enable status of Evaluation Case 10. Evaluation Case 10 refers to the situation where the dP-based and timer-based soot values at the end of soot accumulation phase >= C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Start_Thr_dP kPa and C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Start_Thr_Model seconds, respectively, and the increase in timer-based soot model > C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Incr_Thr_Model seconds (S) while the increase in dP-based model <= C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Incr_Thr_dP kPa (U).

Name: C_SFD_TFR_Box_5_6_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: A calibratable parameter indicating the enable status of Evaluation Cases 5 and 6. Evaluation Case 5 refers to the situation where the dP-based soot amount at the end of DeSoot >= C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Start_Thr_dP kPa (U) and the timer-based soot amount < C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Start_Thr_Model (S) seconds while both the increases in dP-based and timer-based soot levels are less than C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Incr_Thr_dP kPa (U) and C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Incr_Thr_Model (U) seconds, respectively. Evaluation Case 6 is similar to Evaluation Case 5 while the difference is the timer-based soot level increase > C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Incr_Thr_Model seconds (S).

Name: C_SFD_TFR_Box_8_12_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: A calibratable parameter indicating the enable status of Evaluation Cases 8 and 12. Both Cases 8 and 12 share the same assumption where the increase in dP-based soot level > C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Incr_Thr_dP kPa (S) while the increase in the timer-based soot level <= C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Incr_Thr_Model seconds (U). The difference between the two is that Case 12 implies both dP-based and timer-based soot levels at the end of soot accumulation phase < C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Start_Thr_dP kPa (S) and C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Start_Thr_Model seconds (S), respectively, while in Case 8, only the timer-based soot level at the end of soot accumulation phase < C_SFD_TFR_Soot_Start_Thr_Model seconds (U).

Name: C_SFD_TFR_Filter_Const
Fieldvalues.Name: A calibratable parameter indicating a filter constant for a filter used on the ratio between the increase in dP-based soot level and the increase in timer-based soot level during soot accumulation period after the wait period. This filter helps reduce the effect of a step change. A step change in the ratio from 1 to the OBD limit ratio, will trigger an error when the condition exist for two consecutive events.

Name: C_SFD_TFR_ID

Name: C_SFD_TFR_MaxFiltLim

Name: C_SFD_TFR_MinFiltLim
Fieldvalues.Name: A calibratable parameter used as a minimum limit for the ratio between the increase in dP-based soot level and the increase in timer-based soot level. This limit is used to increase the likelihood that the diagnostic will run and set/clear DPF TFR error following corrective service action.

Name: C_SFD_TFR_Ratio_Thr
Fieldvalues.Name: A calibratable parameter indicating the maximum allowable ratio between the increase in dP-based soot level and the increase in timer-based soot-level during soot accumulation period. The increases are measured after the wait period. Any value exceeding this threshold will result in the DPF TFR error being set.

Fieldvalues.Name:
This table contains the maximum structural torque limit of the engine. It acts as the starting point for engine protection derates and is also used by engine manager as an absolute torque limit not to be exceeded.



This torque limit table is associated with the engine speed axis, C_STRC_MaxLoadEngineSpeedX.



Not required by SRS. Calibrated by design.



Default = { 200, 200, 200, 200, 200,

200, 200, 200, 200, 200,

200, 200, 200, 200, 200,

200, 200, 200, 200, 200,

200}
AxisX.Name:
This calibration is intended to represent the table of engine speeds associated with the maximum engine structural torque limit table, C_STRC_MaxLoadTorqueTbl, speed axis.



Not required by SRS. Calibrated by design.



Default = { 0, 500, 1000, 1100, 1200,

1300, 1400, 1500, 1600, 1700,

1800, 1900, 2000, 2100, 2200,

2500, 4000, 6000, 8000, 10000,

12000 }

Name: ECM_Active_Error_Index
Fieldvalues.Name:
Parameter or table that stores the active error_index retrieved from CFTR_ErrorIndexTable. It only stores one of the error_index of the errors, if multiple errors that mapped to the same service fault code happens.

0 indicates the last entry of the table

This table is closely related to ECM_Active_Fault_Count. It is indexed as 1 to 1 to this table.

Example:
ECM_Active_Error_Index[0] = 12
ECM_Active_Fault_Count[0] contains the fault_count of ECM_Active_Error_Index[0]. It is not counting on the error, but it is counting on the fault code which is mapped from CFTR_Available_Fault_Table[ECM_Active_Error_Index[0]]



Maximum of 31 error_index.

Name: ECM_Active_Fault_Count
Fieldvalues.Name:
Parameter or table that stores fault_count information of the currently active fault_code. The fault_count gets incremented when there is a transition from inactive service fault (not error) to active service fault

0 indicates the last entry of the table

This table is closely related to ECM_Active_Error_Index. It is indexed as 1 to 1 to this table.

Example:
ECM_Active_Error_Index[0] = 12
ECM_Active_Fault_Count[0] contains the fault_count of ECM_Active_Error_Index[0]. It is not counting on the error, but it is counting on the fault code which is mapped from CFTR_Available_Fault_Table[ECM_Active_Error_Index[0]]



Maximum of 31 error_index.

Name: ECM_Active_Index_Count
Fieldvalues.Name: Parameter or table that stores number of active or inactive errors with the same fault code, in which either one of these error are currently active

Name: ECM_Inactive_Error_Index
Fieldvalues.Name:
Parameter or table that stores the inactive error_index retrieved from CFTR_ErrorIndexTable. It only stores one of the error_index of the errors, if multiple errors that mapped to the same service fault code happens.

0 indicates the last entry of the table

This table is closely related to ECM_Inactive_Fault_Count. It is indexed as 1 to 1 to this table.

Example:
ECM_Inactive_Error_Index[0] = 12
ECM_Inactive_Fault_Count[0] contains the fault_count of ECM_Inactive_Error_Index[0]. It is not counting on the error, but it is counting on the fault code which is mapped from CFTR_Available_Fault_Table[ECM_Inactive_Error_Index[0]]



Maximum of 31 error_index.

Name: ECM_Inactive_Fault_Count
Fieldvalues.Name:
Parameter or table that stores fault_count information of the currently inactive fault_code. The fault_count does not get incremented when there is a transition from active service fault (not error) to inactive service fault. It also does not get decremented when the process countdown

0 indicates the last entry of the table

This table is closely related to ECM_Inactive_Error_Index. It is indexed as 1 to 1 to this table.

Example:
ECM_Inactive_Error_Index[0] = 12
ECM_Inactive_Fault_Count[0] contains the fault_count of ECM_Inactive_Error_Index[0]. It is not counting on the error, but it is counting on the fault code which is mapped from CFTR_Available_Fault_Table[ECM_Inactive_Error_Index[0]]



Maximum of 31 error_index.

Name: GTIS_CalibrationVersion
Fieldvalues.Name:
Calibration version numbers are stored as 4-byte integer values with display format of ""dot_notation"". The numbers would be represented visually as four, one byte release numbers separated by dots. It is important the the release level numbers be 00-99 decimal in order to meet CES 14619.

For example, version 3.2.79.23 would be stored in an integer whose hexadecimal representation is 03024F17.

Name: GTIS_EndBootLoaderVersion
Fieldvalues.Name: 4 byte Boot Loader Version which the calibration loaded is compatible with.  This value along with Boot_Loader_Version enable tools to understand if the calibration to be downloaded to the ECM is compatible with the boot loader stored in the ECM. This is a non-imaged Cal since the GCC for GTIS 4.5+ will need an index table reference to verify this value vs the compatibility header records.  Stored as a hex representation of x.y.z.w format where each value is 1 byte, 0 - 0xFF (or 0 - 255).

Name: GTIS_StartBootLoaderVersion
Fieldvalues.Name: Boot Loader Version which the calibration loaded is compatible with.  This value along with End_Boot_Loader_Version enable tools to understand if the calibration to be downloaded to the ECM is compatible with the boot loader stored in the ECM. This is a non-imaged Cal since the GCC for GTIS 4.5+ will need an index table reference to verify this value vs the compatibility header records. Stored as a hex representation of x.y.z.w format where each value is 1 byte, 0 - 0xFF (or 0 - 255).

This is an one dimensional array whose index is same as the error_index. The zero element of the array is unused. This is to synchronize with other legacy OBD arrays based on No. of Errors in the system.

Name: OBD_Fault_Status_Table
Fieldvalues.Name:
A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index and contains the current error state for each OBD Error in the system.

The valid error states are defined as the following:
[b7......b0]
ACTIVE xxxx xxx1
INACTIVE xxxx xxx0
CONFIRMED xxxx xx1x
OBD PENDING xxxx x1xx
PERMANENT xxxx 1xxx
MONCOMPLETESTATUS xxx1 xxxx
Non_Erasable OBD Error xx1x xxxx
OBD_Diagnostic_Disabled x1xx xxxx
OBD / non-OBD 1xxx xxxx

OBD_Group_MIL_On[x] = (READY) 1 (At least one error among all errors which are mapped to X group caused MIL to ON since last DTC clear)
OBD_Group_MIL_On[x] = (NOT READY) 0 (All errors which are mapped to X group never caused MIL to ON since last DTC clear)

EX_GAS_SENSOR 3
FUEL_SYSTEM 4

Name: OBD_Similar_Eng_Data
Fieldvalues.Name: It is an array of structure that contains error index, engine speed,. percentage load, and engine status (cold/warm) for a particular error index when similar conditions exists and is specified in the  C_OBD_SimilarCondType table. With a value of 1 in C_OBD_SimilarCondType table, data would be gathered in OBD_Similar_Eng_Data array.

Name: OBD_Status_Flag
Fieldvalues.Name:
A one dimensional array whose index is the same as error_index.
This is a bitmapped parameter to replace/indicate OBD_ReadinessStatus,
OBD_WarmupCycCompletion_Flag, OBD error active/inactive in previous operation cycle and scan tool command received/not received.
OBD_Err_Act_Warmbt_Detected : Is used to detect error active after warmboot.
OBD_Drive_Cycle_In_Bucket1: Is used to detect Drive cycle while in Bucket1
The valid states are defined as the following:
[b7??..b0]
OBD_ReadinessStatus READY xxxx xxx1
OBD_ReadinessStatus NOT READY xxxx xxx0
OBD_WarmupCycCompletion_Flag xxxx xx1x
OBD_Error_Active _Prev_OprCyc xxxx x1xx
OBD_Error_Inactive _Prev_OprCyc xxxx x0xx
SCAN_TOOL_COMMAND_RECVD xxxx 1xxx
SCAN_TOOL_COMMAND_NOT_RECVD xxxx 0xxx
OBD_Err_Act_Warmbt_Detected xxx1 xxxx
OBD_Drive_Cycle_In_Bucket1 xx1x xxxx

{This indicates whether OBD_SuccessfulWarmup

Name: OBD_SuccessfulOprCycles
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is same as error_index. This is the number of consecutive operation cycles for each OBD error that should occur without the error becoming active.  Used to determine when to clear the permanent status and turn off the MIL.

Name: OBD_SuccessfulWarmupCycles
Fieldvalues.Name: A one dimensional array whose index is same as error_index. This is the number of consecutive warmup cycles (or alternative event, when enabled) for each OBD error that should occur without the error becoming active. Used to determine when to clear the confirmed status.

Name: OBD_Warmup_Cyc_Dur
Fieldvalues.Name: This is the time duration that elapsed in current warmup Cycle. This information is used to track when to increment OBD_Error_Mem_Clr_WarmupCycle.

Name: OBD_Warmup_Cyc_Since_DTC_Clr
Fieldvalues.Name:
Total number of warmup cycles that have occurred since the last Erase OBD Faults call or calibration reflash.
This will be incremented till 250 and hold the value until next Erase OBD Fault occurs.
Will be resetted to zero when Erase OBD Fault call occurs.

Name: T_EDC_Collector_Enable
Fieldvalues.Name: Enables/disables the engineering data collector functionality of the ECM.

Name: T_EDC_Collector_ID_Table
Fieldvalues.Name: List of public data identifiers to be saved for each data collector record.

Name: T_EDC_Collector_Interrupt_ID
Fieldvalues.Name:
Each value in the table corresponds to an interrupt. Interrupts include: EPS=1, VSS=2, JCOM=3, and PIT=4. When the selected interrupt occurs, a complete sample may be collected, subject to other conditions, such as the state of T_EDC_Collector_Trigger.

Used as argument ""event"" for XMGR_register call to Execution Manager.



Note: To be compatible with the legacy (GTIS 3.6) data collector the value of 0 shall indicate that the collector is configured to collect data at the EPS interrupt. When the value is 1 the data shall be collected at the PIT. This will be removed when the legacy data collector meets the new vision interface (described above). The Comm Agent Base will make the appropriate conversion to the values that the execution manager expects to see at the interface.

Name: T_EDC_Collector_Interval
Fieldvalues.Name:
Value k indicates that k-1 interrupts are to be ignored, then on every kth interrupt, a complete sample may be taken, subject to other conditions, such as the state of T_EDC_Collector_Trigger.

Used as argumet ""occurrance"" for XMGR_register call to Execution Manager.

Name: T_EDC_Collector_Offset
Fieldvalues.Name:
-- offset description (parameter input into XMGR_register)

For events 3 (RT exec), 4 (engine speed exec), and 5 (vehicle speed exec) the offset is the number of minor frames to wait before starting the cyclical execution every occurrence number of minor frames. Offset is used to define a rate group for a task. It can exceed a theoretical major frame (though there is no specific major frame enforced by the execution manager) for which the rate group would be the offset%occurrence.

Name: T_EDC_Collector_Stop_Mode
Fieldvalues.Name:
Indicator as to how much data is to be recorded following occurrence of T_EDC_Collector_Trigger.

The modes are:

0-- Stop_On_Trigger: data collection stops immediately when T_EDC_Collector_Trigger becomes TRUE.

1--Fill_Half_On_Trigger: following T_EDC_Collector_Trigger becoming TRUE, an additional number of samples is collected, the number being half the capacity of the buffer.

2--Fill_Full_On_Trigger: following T_EDC_Collector_Trigger becoming TRUE, an additional number of samples is collected, the number being the entire capacity of the buffer.

Name: T_EDC_Collector_Trigger
Fieldvalues.Name: This trigger initiates collection of data into the GTIS_Collector_Buffer for engineering use. Only complete samples are collected. A complete sample is the collection of data from every element that is specified in the T_EDC_Collector_Name_Table.

Name: V_Sensor_Supply_1_Config
Fieldvalues.Name:
This structure configures the Voltage Sensor Supplies to operate within a user defined range, and adds the ability to turn the Voltage Sensor Supply monitoring on and off, depening on the module configurations.

Parameters that must be configured are


min_thd_count_lower_limit - to be set to a value, in a2d counts, at which point a diagnostic low error will be set.

min_thd_count_upper_limit - to be set to a value, in a2d counts, at which point a diagnostic low error will be cleared.

max_thd_count_lower_limit - to be set to a value, in a2d counts, at which point a diagnostic high error will be cleared.

max_thd_count_upper_limit - to be set to a value, in a2d counts, at which point a diagnostic high error will be set

sensor_enable - Enables/Disables the processing of this particular Sensor Supply.
0 = disabled
1 = enabled

sensor_id - This is the actual RLOC (harware id) that this sensor supply is connected to. (ie Analog channel, discrete channel, etc)

type - Determines what type of sensor reading s

Name: application_code_checksum_table
Fieldvalues.Name:
This is a constant table which is filled in by the build environment with the checksum of code between the various AB_CodeBlock labels. The first element of the table is the number of populated code blocks. The second element is reserved for use by the Autobuild as a complement to the checksum of the block which contains this table.

Each additional three elements are the start address, exclusive end address, and checksum for a block.

Name: application_crc_block_table
Fieldvalues.Name:
This is a constant table which is filled in by the build environment with the addresses from the crc_blockX_subY_start and crc_blockX_subY_end labels (link map). The first element of the table is the number of populated crc blocks. The second element is reserved to be common with the application_code_checksum_table.

Each additional three array elements are:
[1] the corresponding checksum number (first byte) and the number of sublocks (second byte) associated with that checksum, plus 2 reserved bytes,
[2] the start address as 4 bytes.
[3] the exclusive end address of the subblocks.

The calculated checksum values are stored in separate calibration or trim data.

FolderName: To be used only when no acronym is known for the item.\
Fieldvalues.Name:
This table contains the resource location for analog to digital converter channel. By default, the values defined in the table is for dcx. For other application, this table has to be overwritten by the user.

The index for this table is an RLOC.
The data at a particular index is the analog input channel assigned to that RLOC.

Name: os_pwm_outputs
Fieldvalues.Name:
Contains an array of PWM output mappings for all PWMs

Each entry in this array has the following structure elements.
Element 1: RLOC of the PWM
Element 2: Channel of the device
Element 3: Device (0 = eTPUA, 1 = eTPUB, 2 = EMIOS, 3 =BM, 4 = DISCO, 5 = HB, 6 = TACH )
Element 4: Inversion
Element 5: RLOC for Feedback
Element 6: Diagnostic channel for Feedback;
Element 7: Diagnostic device for Feedback (0 = eTPUA, 1 = eTPUB, 2 = EMIOS, 3 =BM, 4 = DISCO, 5 = HB, 6 = TACH )
Element 8: Feedback Inversion
Element 9: On error persistence Count for eTPU OFB only
Element 10: Off error persistence Count for eTPU OFB only
Element 11: Time delay for eTPU OFB only
Element 12: Retry limit
